LISTERIOSIS - SINGAPORE: AUSTRALIAN ROCKMELONS, NOT
***************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Sat 10 Mar 2018
Source: Straits Times [edited]
http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/listeria-case-at-sgh-not-linked-to-contaminated-rockmelons-moh


Health authorities say there is no link between a patient who was seen at the Singapore General Hospital (SGH) for listeriosis and the consumption of contaminated rockmelons from Australia, according to preliminary investigations.

The Ministry of Health (MOH) told The Straits Times on Friday [9 Mar 2018] that there is still no report of anyone here having contracted the bacterial disease as a result of eating the rockmelons, which have made 17 people ill in Australia and killed 4. All rockmelons from Australia are in the process of being recalled by authorities.

The ministry said it was notified by SGH of a case of listeriosis on Tue 6 Mar 2018. Further tests are ongoing to determine the source of infection.

A WhatsApp message that circulated on Friday [9 Mar 2018] claimed that someone who ate rockmelons from Sheng Siong[*] ended up as the "first case of listeria in SGH."

The outbreak in Australia is linked to contaminated rockmelons from a farm in New South Wales. Consignments of melons from the farm were found to have been exported to Singapore.

There is an incubation period of between 3 and 70 days after consuming _Listeria_-contaminated food. Consumers should seek medical attention as early as possible if they develop fever and muscle aches that are preceded by diarrhoea or other gastrointestinal symptoms appearing within 70 days of eating Australian rockmelon, the ministry said.

Doctors have been asked to refer suspected cases of listeriosis for testing and treatment and to notify MOH of suspected cases. "We will continue to monitor the situation closely," said the MOH spokesman.

